Dear Aliquippa School District Community,

It is with great sadness to announce our cheerleader sponsor, Ms. Shawnte Olden, passed away yesterday. She was a proud Aliquippa graduate who will be deeply missed by the students and staff she worked with.

Counselors will be available for all students and staff at the JSHS Monday, September 14, 2020 9:00 AM - 3:00 PM.

As the District expresses its deep sympathy, please remember her and her family in your thoughts and prayers.

Peter M. Carbone, Ed.D.
Superintendent of Schools

Mr. Beaver County
May 18 at 1:22 PM ¬∑

It‚Äôs time to meet Takeyman Tucker, a multi-talented Senior from Aliquippa High School ‚Äì and our next contestant for Mr. Beaver County! Takeyman serves as the Aliquippa Senior class Treasurer, as well as the President of the National Honor Society program (which he has been part of for 6 years). Takeyman has been keeping busy as a 5-year member of the Talent Search Program and a 2-year member or the Youth Ambassadors Program. He also has competed for two years as a member of the Aliquippa Track & Field Team! During his free time, Takeyman enjoys taking photos and developing his talents in Photography. After graduation, Takeyman plans to attend Florida Agricultural and Mechanical University for Business Marketing with a Minor in Culinary Arts. Don't miss the TikTok we created just for him here: https://www.tiktok.com/@theprevnet/video/6828217231302937862 and be sure to keep an eye on our The Prevention Network & CLASS Academy Instagram page for a feature on Takeyman too: https://www.instagram.com/theprevnet/ Good Luck Takeyman!! #Seniors2020 #MrBC2020

post_text: The Beaver County School Districts and the Career and Technology Center continue to work together as we receive guidance from our state and federal leaders. Today, Governor Wolf announced that all schools will remain closed for the remainder of the 2019-2020 academic year. Therefore, all Beaver County school facilities are closed and events cancelled through the end of the school year. While much uncertainty still exists, this announcement will allow families to plan for their needs in the coming months. All schools will continue to provide continuity of education and meals through at least the last regularly scheduled day of school. We understand that this is heartbreaking for the Class of 2020, but please be patient as we seek additional guidance from our state leaders regarding graduation and other special events. We appreciate your patience and support during this closure and we will continue to provide updates as we move forward together.

February 21 at 10:39 AM ¬∑

If you should see Isaiah Towler, Carpentry student from Aliquippa School District, make sure you tell him CONGRATULATIONS! Isaiah was recently accepted to not only attend Indiana University of Pennsylvania (IUP) but, he will also be playing IUP Football, majoring in Safety Science. Isaiah said that making the decision to enroll in Carpentry was a good move for him. His decision to major in 'Safety' was largely impart from a presentation from Mac Safety Consultants, who presents to Mr. Liptak's students annually about construction site safety. According to Mr. Liptak, Isaiah is one of the top carpenter's he has in his program and is excited about his future managing sites and keeping people safe on the job. Awesome!
#rethinkCTCeducation #eliminatingtheskillgap #CTEinPA #skilledtrades #PASuccess #constructioncareers

Aliquippa School District has partnered with Highmark Caring Place, whose core purpose is to make a difference in the lives of grieving children. We will be working with the Caring Place to provide Grief Groups in grades K-12. The Groups will be held during the school day with the School Counselor at your school, will meet approximately 8-10 times over the course a couple months, and will guide your child through the grief process.

If you are interested or have questions about your child participating in this program, please contact your child‚Äôs School Counselor at 724 - 857- 7500.

post_text:
Aliquippa Cheerleaders helping out the elementary school:

"The Power Pak Program provides healthy, tasty foods that school-aged children take home on weekends during the school year. The Power ‚ÄúPak‚Äù contains nutritious, easy-to-prepare foods, as well as snacks. The Pak breaks down into four healthy meals and two snacks. Through partnerships with local school districts, the food is stored in participating schools‚Äô cafeterias. Leak proof, low density, bags are then packed by school nutrition staff and volunteers. The ‚ÄúPaks‚Äù are discreetly distributed to eligible children on Fridays or before school breaks."

July 23, 2019 at 3:42 PM ¬∑

üì¢Attention Aliquippa! Our Drug Free Aliquippa Youth Coalition Leaders have been doing BIG THINGS! üì¢

Last week, 5 of our teen leaders attended CADCA's MidYear Forum in DALLAS, TEXAS. This conference brought over 2,200 people together and there were 500 (üì¢FIVE. HUNDRED.üì¢) Youth leaders from across the country!!! These teens were gaining leadership skills that they will use to guide their peers and community members this year.

We spent a week together learning about community engagement and empowerment. Incredible!

We even went to downtown Dallas to visit the site of the JFK Assassination. Even though it's summer, they're still learning and experiencing new things!

Show them some love - and get ready for big things this year. We need your support, Aliquippa! #DrugFreeAliquippa

After playing 5 games in 10 days our Quips ran into a very good team in New Brighton and even though we started fast with a homerun from Tyke Hayes scoring Arison Walker to go ahead 2 to 0 to start the game. It was rough going after that New Brighton got going and the pitching settled down and our Quips found hitting hard to come by and the errors came calling on defense. The lions went ahead and never looked back scoring 8 runs in 2 innings before the Quips got a inside the park homerun from James Gilbert to add one more run to close out the Quips scoring at 3. The final score was 11 to 3 before the üåß and üå© stopped the game after 5 innings. Great finish to a long year Great job Quips enjoy the rest of your summer!

#FINISHED 4TH OUT OF 14 TEAMS!

I am pleased to announce that Aliquippa School District will receive a nearly $25,000 grant through the Pennsylvania Department of Education‚Äôs competitive Safe Schools Targeted grant program. These funds can be used to purchase safety and security-related equipment and are designed to aid schools in getting the resources they need to create a safe learning environment for students.

It is critical for all local schools to evaluate how we can better protect students and make our school buildings a safe environment for learning, and I applaud all of the local districts over the past year who submitted applications for this program to boost school safety.

More information on school safety measures is available online at https://www.pasenategop.caom/school-safety/.

Nyhlese Lowe, Cosmetology II student from Aliquippa School District, was one of a few to observe Ms. Beke up close as she briefly demonstrated her technique to those few who managed to get on the stage. At the end of her session, Nyhlese and other Cosmetology students from our program and other CTC's won various products through a raffle. A very positive message for future professionals in the Cosmetology Industry!

post_text: Army recruiters came to Aliquippa Jr/Sr High School physical education classes and assisted the Phys Ed department with an obstacle course that students had to complete as quickly as possible. Students competed against each other and the quickest times were given prizes. The obstacle course was designed to simulate an Army training course and students had to avoid dodge balls from enemies while they were completing it. Army recruiters also talked with students about pursuing careers in the military after high school.

Penn State Talent Search
February 6, 2019 at 4:30 PM ¬∑

When I grow up, I want to be a mechanical engineer. There‚Äôs not a lot of female mechanical engineers, like anywhere, so I really want to be one. My Granny said, ‚ÄòI can see you being an engineer,‚Äô and so can my mom. I think it is important that there are female mechanical engineers so that you can show other little girls you can be something even if there‚Äôs not a lot of girls [doing it already.] Usually you see men as mechanical engineers, you don‚Äôt see women. You can tell little girls, ‚Äòyou can be this too.‚Äô

Jahnauri is an eighth grade Penn State Talent Search student at Aliquippa School District . Her academic excellence has been recognized with the Distinguished Honor Roll. Jahnauri is thankful for both the cultural and explorational field trip opportunities organized by her counselor, Karen Sheffield.
#IAmTrio #TRIOWORKS #Education #girlsinstem

post_text: The Aliquippa School District had Beaver County Emergency Services coordinate an entire day of Active Shooter Training with District staff, the Beaver County District Attorney‚Äôs Office, the Beaver County Sheriff‚Äôs Department and the Aliquippa Police Department. The training included Active Shooter background, best practices procedures and case studies, followed by more specific instruction on sheltering, evacuation, decision making, self-defense and tactical awareness. During this same time Aliquippa Police Department received tactical response updates and training (RAIDER Training). Following the aforementioned training all of the above agencies conducted two Active Shooter full scale exercises. Personnel in attendance were in agreement that the training and exercises were successful and left everyone better prepared to respond to real life emergencies at the school district, should they occur.

shared_text:
Drug Free Aliquippa
February 7, 2018 at 10:43 PM ¬∑

Aliquippa!!! Did you know that 4 of our high school students are in Washington, D.C. participating in a NATIONAL youth leadership conference focusing on drug and alcohol prevention and advocacy?

Today, Alfred, Tyrese, Kataijah and Christina went to our Nation's Capitol to speak to members of Congress about why the Drug Free Communities grant program and the Drug Free Aliquippa Youth Coalition matter to them. These young leaders are forward thinking and passionate. They want CHANGE for Aliquippa and a BETTER community for their peers. We are so proud of them!!!

Thank you to CADCA for facilitating this opportunity.

#Aliquippa #DrugFreeAliquippa #CADCAForum #youthleadership

post_text: Last year on September 26, Central Valley School District, community, Mr. Rowe (Principal at Hopewell HS), and his family lost their little superhero Charlie Rowe to pediatric cancer. post_text: The Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) covers uninsured kids and teens up to age 19. With more than 139,000 uninsured children in Pennsylvania, this is great news for families! CHIP provides quality, comprehensive health insurance for routine doctor visits, prescriptions, dental, eye care, eyeglasses, mental health and much more. CHIP covers uninsured kids who are not eligible for Medical Assistance. For most families, CHIP is free - for others, it is low cost. Click the link below for more information.

Pedro Rivera, Pennsylvania Secretary of Education, visited the Aliquippa Junior/Senior High School on Friday, January 20, 2017 as part of his Schools that Teach Tour. Rivera discussed his Future Ready PA Index, a new rating system for the state‚Äôs public schools that the Pennsylvania Department of Education hopes to have ready for implementation in the fall of 2018.

Additional guests in attendance were Eric Rosendale (Beaver Valley Intermediate Unit Director), David Wytiaz (Director of the Beaver County Career and Technology Center), Donna Nugent (Superintendent of the Beaver Falls School District), Tammy Adams (Superintendent of the South Side School District(, David Lozier (Beaver County District Attorney), State Representative Robert Matzie, Aliquippa Mayor Dwan Walker, and the Aliquippa School Board, including Terry Swanson, Elverna Cuffie, Nicole Bible, Catherine Colalella, Sandy Gill, and Tina Price-Genes.

post_text: Welcome to the Official page for Aliquippa School District. We are your source for everything Quip, along with our website QuipSD.org. To make things easier, this page is for both the Aliquippa Elementary School and the Aliquippa Jr./Sr. High School. Our page is here to help strengthen the bond between the Aliquippa School District and the community. Go Quips!
